<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
    <head>
        <title>MyCSS Eg</title>
        <style>
            h1{
                color:blue;
            }
            div div p{
                color:red;
            }
            #myh2,.veg{
                color:green
            }
            .fruit{
                color:blue;
            }
        </style>
    </head>
    <body>
        <h1>H1 Hello World</h1>
        <p>Para outside</p>
        <div>
            <p>Para inside div</p>
            <div>
                <p>Para in div in div</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <h2 id="myh2">H2 Tag</h2>
        <ul>
            <li class="veg">Carrot</li>
            <li class="veg">Potato</li>
            <li class="fruit">Apple</li>
            <li class="fruit">Orange</li>
            <li class="fruit">Guava</li>
            <li class="veg">Onion</li>
        </ul>
    </body>
</html>




The Type Selectors: h1 {    color: #36CFFF; }
The Universal Selectors: * {   color: #000000; }
The Descendant Selectors: This style rule will apply to <em> element only when it lies inside <ul> tag.  ul em {   color: #000000;  }
The Class Selectors: .black {   color: #000000;  }  
h1.black {   color: #000000;  }
The ID Selectors: #black {   color: #000000;  }
h1#black {   color: #000000;  }
#black h2 {   color: #000000;  } (All level 2 headings will be displayed in black color only when those headings will lie with in tags having id as black)
The Child Selectors: body > p {   color: #000000;  } (This rule will render all the paragraphs in black if they are direct child of <body> element. Other paragraphs put inside other elements like <div> or <td> etc. would not have any effect of this rule.)
Grouping Selectors: h1, h2, h3 { color: #36C; font-weight: normal;}


